# Flutter Core Best Practices

Use these as default implementation standards for this repository.
Project-specific rules remain authoritative when stricter.

## Code quality
- Prefer clear, maintainable code over clever abstractions.
- Keep functions focused and reasonably short.
- Use descriptive names; avoid abbreviations.
- Add comments only when explaining non-obvious intent.

## Dart correctness
- Keep code soundly null-safe; avoid unnecessary `!`.
- Use `async`/`await` with explicit error handling (`try/catch`) for fallible work.
- Prefer exhaustive `switch` statements/expressions where applicable.
- Do not silently swallow exceptions.

## Flutter UI and performance
- Compose UI from small widgets; avoid oversized `build()` methods.
- Avoid expensive work in `build()` (network calls, heavy computation).
- Use `const` constructors/widgets where possible.
- Use lazy builders (`ListView.builder`, `SliverList`, `GridView.builder`) for long collections.

## Architecture and state
- Follow feature-oriented organization and separation of concerns:
  presentation, domain, data, core.
- Prefer constructor dependency injection and repository abstractions.
- In this project, follow the `CommonCubit` pattern and keep one-off UI actions
  in custom state/events.

## Testing and tooling
- Add/update tests for behavior changes when practical.
- Keep tests deterministic with clear Arrange-Act-Assert structure.
- After changing l10n/codegen inputs, run required generators:
  `flutter gen-l10n` and/or
  `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs`.
